= Teaching Statement

My goal as an educator aligns closely with the University of Oslo's commitment to fostering an inclusive and innovative learning environment that prepares students to address global challenges. I strive to make economics accessible by bridging complex theories with real-world applications, ensuring clarity without sacrificing rigor. This approach supports the Department of Economics' focus on behavioral economics and the interplay of knowledge, social interactions, and moral norms by enabling students to grasp how these elements shape economic decision-making.

My educational philosophy rests on two core principles: clarity and active learning. I translate technical economic language into intuitive concepts, teaching in a dual-language fashion—both formal and accessible—to engage diverse student backgrounds and learning styles. Complementing this, I incorporate hands-on workshops where students tackle problems collaboratively, fostering an interactive atmosphere that reflects the department's emphasis on applied understanding and interdisciplinary solutions.

This pedagogical method not only enhances comprehension but also encourages students to practice ethical and innovative thinking, aligning with the university's values of academic freedom, high ethical standards, and societal engagement. In previous courses, such as Price Theory, this strategy yielded high student satisfaction and measurable achievement, validating its effectiveness.

Ultimately, my teaching aims to empower students with analytical tools to critically evaluate economic phenomena within societal contexts, contributing to the university's mission to educate leaders who can create a better world. My commitment to fostering diversity and inclusive dialogue complements the department’s goals and prepares students to tackle socio-economic challenges innovatively and ethically.
